[;1m[0m[;1m[0m  [;1mDebugging[0m: after shebang line add "set - n" (or what have you) -            
  that will allow you to run your script without executing it, only           
  checking for any errors.                                                    
                                                                              
  There are a number of options that can be used for debugging purposes:      
                                                                              
  • [;1mset -n (bash -n)[0m just checks for syntax                                   
  • [;1mset -x (bash -x)[0m echos all commands after running them                    
  • [;1mset -v (bash -v)[0m echos all commands before running them                   
  • [;1mset -u (bash -u)[0m causes the shell to treat using unset variables          
  as an error                                                                 
  • [;1mset -e (bash -e)[0m causes the script to exit immediately upon any           
  non-zero exit status (on any failures).                                     
                                                                              
  where the [;1mset[0m command is used inside the script (with a [;1m+[0m sign              
  behavior is reversed) and the second form, giving an option to [;1mbash[0m,        
  is invoked when running the script from the command line.                   
                                                                              
[;1m[0m[;1m[0m  [;1m-x[0m                                                                          
                                                                              
                                                                              
  You can also specify the above, not directly in your script but when        
  calling the script with the bash command...                                 
                                                                              
  bash -x myscript.sj                                                         
                                                                              
  This isn't as portable though.                                              
                                                                              
